From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: V5 Project <v5@example.invalid>
Date: Sat, 16 May 2026 22:05:00 +0800
Subject: [PATCH] v5: keep sent datagram state on duplicate queue

The V5 native LinuxCNC EtherCAT path uses two cyclic domain datagrams
(LWR/LRD) through IgH's generic backend. When a valid process-data reply is
late enough that the next servo cycle queues the same domain datagram again,
upstream IgH detects the duplicate queue entry, increments skip_count, and
then forcibly changes the datagram state back to EC_DATAGRAM_QUEUED. The code
comment notes that this can cause an unmatched datagram.

On the Zynq GEM + SV630N chain, that is exactly the observed failure chain:
domain datagram SKIPPED, then UNMATCHED, then Domain 0 WKC drops 0/10 and
recovers to 10/10. Preserve EC_DATAGRAM_SENT for an already-queued sent
datagram so the late reply can still match by index/type/size and be dequeued
normally. Non-sent duplicate entries keep the existing recovery behavior.

This keeps the motion path LinuxCNC/IgH/lcec-native and avoids masking WKC or
servo faults in userspace.
---
 master/master.c | 9 ++++++++-
 1 file changed, 8 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/master/master.c b/master/master.c
index 4444444..5555555 100644
--- a/master/master.c
+++ b/master/master.c
@@ -979,7 +979,14 @@ void ec_master_queue_datagram(
             EC_MASTER_DBG(master, 1,
                     "Datagram %p already queued (skipping).\n", datagram);
 #endif
-            datagram->state = EC_DATAGRAM_QUEUED;
+            /*
+             * V5 native EtherCAT: if a cyclic domain datagram is still
+             * waiting for its reply, do not turn it back into QUEUED. Keeping
+             * SENT lets a late but valid reply match instead of becoming a
+             * self-induced UNMATCHED datagram.
+             */
+            if (datagram->state != EC_DATAGRAM_SENT)
+                datagram->state = EC_DATAGRAM_QUEUED;
             return;
         }
     }
